# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: y-fast-trie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A **bit array** (also known as **bit map**, **bit set**, **bit string**, or **bit vector**) is an array data structure that compactly stores bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It can be used to implement a simple set data structure.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A bit array is effective at exploiting bit-level parallelism in hardware to perform operations quickly.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A typical bit array stores *kw* bits, where *w* is the number of bits in the unit of storage, such as a byte or word, and *k* is some positive integer.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] If *w* does not divide the number of bits to be stored, some space is wasted due to internal fragmentation.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A bit array is a mapping from some domain (almost always a range of integers) to values in the set $\{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The values can be interpreted as dark/light, absent/present, locked/unlocked, valid/invalid, et cetera.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The point is that there are only two possible values, so they can be stored in one bit.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] As with other arrays, the access to a single bit can be managed by applying an index to the array.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Assuming its size (or length) to be *n* bits, the array can be used to specify a subset of the domain (e.g. $\{0,1,2,...,n-1\}$ ), where a 1-bit indicates the presence and a 0-bit the absence of a number in the set.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] This set data structure uses about *n*/*w* words of space, where *w* is the number of bits in each machine word.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Whether the least significant bit (of the word) or the most significant bit indicates the smallest-index number is largely irrelevant, but the former tends to be preferred (on little-endian machines).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A finite binary relation may be represented by a bit array called a logical matrix.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In the calculus of relations, these arrays are composed with matrix multiplication where the arithmetic is Boolean, and such a composition represents composition of relations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Although most machines are not able to address individual bits in memory, nor have instructions to manipulate single bits, each bit in a word can be singled out and manipulated using bitwise operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] To obtain the bit mask needed for these operations, we can use a bit shift operator to shift the number 1 to the left by the appropriate number of places, as well as bitwise negation if necessary.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] If we wish to iterate through the bits of a bit array, we can do this efficiently using a doubly nested loop that loops through each word, one at a time.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Both of these code samples exhibit ideal locality of reference, which will subsequently receive large performance boost from a data cache.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] If a cache line is *k* words, only about *n*/*wk* cache misses will occur.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] As with character strings it is straightforward to define *length*, *substring*, lexicographical *compare*, *concatenation*, *reverse* operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The implementation of some of these operations is sensitive to endianness.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] If we wish to find the number of 1 bits in a bit array, sometimes called the population count or Hamming weight, there are efficient branch-free algorithms that can compute the number of bits in a word using a series of simple bit operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] We simply run such an algorithm on each word and keep a running total.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] See the Hamming weight article for examples of an efficient implementation.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Vertical flipping of a one-bit-per-pixel image, or some FFT algorithms, requires flipping the bits of individual words (so `b31 b30 ... b0` becomes `b0 ... b30 b31`).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The find first set or *find first one* operation identifies the index or position of the 1-bit with the smallest index in an array, and has widespread hardware support (for arrays not larger than a word) and efficient algorithms for its computation.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] When a priority queue is stored in a bit array, find first one can be used to identify the highest priority element in the queue.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] To expand a word-size *find first one* to longer arrays, one can find the first nonzero word and then run *find first one* on that word.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The related operations *find first zero*, *count leading zeros*, *count leading ones*, *count trailing zeros*, *count trailing ones*, and *log base 2* (see find first set) can also be extended to a bit array in a straightforward manner.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A bit array is the most dense storage for "random" bits, that is, where each bit is equally likely to be 0 or 1, and each one is independent.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] But most data are not random, so it may be possible to store it more compactly.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] For example, the data of a typical fax image is not random and can be compressed.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Run-length encoding is commonly used to compress these long streams.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] However, most compressed data formats are not so easy to access randomly; also by compressing bit arrays too aggressively we run the risk of losing the benefits due to bit-level parallelism (vectorization).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Thus, instead of compressing bit arrays as streams of bits, we might compress them as streams of bytes or words (see Bitmap index (compression)).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] However, bit arrays are not the solution to everything.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Because of their compactness, bit arrays have a number of applications in areas where space or efficiency is at a premium.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Most commonly, they are used to represent a simple group of Boolean flags or an ordered sequence of Boolean values.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays are used for priority queues, where the bit at index *k* is set if and only if *k* is in the queue; this data structure is used, for example, by the Linux kernel, and benefits strongly from a find-first-zero operation in hardware.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays can be used for the allocation of memory pages, inodes, disk sectors, etc.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In such cases, the term *bitmap* may be used.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] However, this term is frequently used to refer to raster images, which may use multiple bits per pixel.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Another application of bit arrays is the Bloom filter, a probabilistic set data structure that can store large sets in a small space in exchange for a small probability of error.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It is also possible to build probabilistic hash tables based on bit arrays that accept either false positives or false negatives.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays and the operations on them are also important for constructing succinct data structures, which use close to the minimum possible space.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In this context, operations like finding the *n*th 1 bit or counting the number of 1 bits up to a certain position become important.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays are also a useful abstraction for examining streams of compressed data, which often contain elements that occupy portions of bytes or are not byte-aligned.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] For example, the compressed Huffman coding representation of a single 8-bit character can be anywhere from 1 to 255 bits long.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In information retrieval, bit arrays are a good representation for the posting lists of very frequent terms.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] If we compute the gaps between adjacent values in a list of strictly increasing integers and encode them using unary coding, the result is a bit array with a 1 bit in the *n*th position if and only if *n* is in the list.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The implied probability of a gap of *n* is 1/2*n*.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] This is also the special case of Golomb coding where the parameter M is 1; this parameter is only normally selected when −log(2 − *p*) / log(1 − *p*) ≤ 1, or roughly the term occurs in at least 38% of documents.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Given a big file of IPv4 addresses (more than 100 GB) — we need to count unique addresses.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays are widely supported in programming languages, either through dedicated interfaces or more general bit manipulation capabilities.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The APL programming language fully supports bit arrays of arbitrary shape and size as a Boolean datatype distinct from integers.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] All major implementations (Dyalog APL, APL2, APL Next, NARS2000, Gnu APL, etc.) pack the bits densely into whatever size the machine word is.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bits may be accessed individually via the usual indexing notation (for example, `A[3]`) as well as through all of the usual primitive functions and operators where they are often operated on using a special case algorithm such as summing the bits via a table lookup of bytes.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The C programming language's *bit fields*, pseudo-objects found in structs with size equal to some number of bits, are in fact small bit arrays; they are limited in that they cannot span words.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Although they give a convenient syntax, the bits are still accessed using bytewise operators on most machines, and they can only be defined statically (like C's static arrays, their sizes are fixed at compile-time).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It is also a common idiom for C programmers to use words as small bit arrays and access bits of them using bit operators.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A widely available header file included in the X11 system, `<xtrapbits.h>`, is “a portable way for systems to define bit field manipulation of arrays of bits.” A more explanatory description of aforementioned approach can be found in the comp.lang.c faq.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In C++, although individual `bool`s typically occupy the same space as a byte or an integer, the STL type `std::vector<bool>` is a partial template specialization in which bits are packed as a space efficiency optimization.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Since bytes (and not bits) are the smallest addressable unit in C++, the `[]` operator does *not* return a reference to an element, but instead returns a proxy reference.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] This might seem a minor point, but it means that `vector<bool>` is *not* a standard STL container, which is why the use of `vector<bool>` is generally discouraged.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Another unique STL class, `std::bitset`, creates a vector of bits fixed at a particular size at compile-time, and in its interface and syntax more resembles the idiomatic use of words as bit sets by C programmers.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It also has some additional power, such as the ability to efficiently count the number of bits that are set.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Like array, the size of `bitset` must be specified at compile time, and cannot be inferred by the compiler.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The Boost C++ Libraries provides a `boost::dynamic_bitset` class whose size is specified at run-time.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The D programming language provides bit arrays in its standard library, Phobos, in `std.bitmanip`.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] As in C++, the [] operator does not return a reference, since individual bits are not directly addressable on most hardware, but instead returns a `bool`.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In Java, the class `BitSet` (`java.util.BitSet`) creates a bit array that is then manipulated with functions named after bitwise operators familiar to C programmers.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Unlike the `bitset` in C++, the Java `BitSet` does not have a "size" state (it has an effectively infinite size, initialized with 0 bits); a bit can be set or tested at any index.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In addition, there is a class `EnumSet` (`java.util.EnumSet`), which represents a Set of values of an enumerated type internally as a bit vector, as a safer alternative to bit fields.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The .NET Framework supplies a `Systems.Collections.BitArray` collection class.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It stores bits using an array of type `int` (each element in the array usually represents 32 bits).
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The class supports random access and bitwise operators, can be iterated over, and its `Length` property can be changed to grow or truncate it.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Although Standard ML has no support for bit arrays, Standard ML of New Jersey has an extension, the `BitArray` structure, in its SML/NJ Library.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] It is not fixed in size and supports set operations and bit operations, including, unusually, shift operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In Perl, strings can be used as expandable bit arrays.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] They can be manipulated using the usual bitwise operators (`~ | & ^`), and individual bits can be tested and set using the *vec* function.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In Ruby, one can access (but not set) a bit of an integer (`Fixnum` or `Bignum`) using the bracket operator (`[]`), as if it were an array of bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Rust supports using native numeric types as fixed-width bit arrays using bitwise operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Third party libraries like `bitvec` provide dedicated interfaces.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Apple's Core Foundation library contains CFBitVector and CFMutableBitVector structures.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] PL/I supports arrays of *bit strings* of arbitrary length, which may be either fixed-length or varying.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The array elements may be *aligned*— each element begins on a byte or word boundary— or *unaligned*— elements immediately follow each other with no padding.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] PL/pgSQL and PostgreSQL's SQL support *bit strings* as native type.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] There are two SQL bit types: bit(*`n`*) and bit varying(*`n`*), where *`n`* is a positive integer.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Hardware description languages such as VHDL, Verilog, and SystemVerilog natively support bit vectors as these are used to model storage elements like flip-flops, hardware busses and hardware signals in general.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In hardware verification languages such as OpenVera, *e* and SystemVerilog, bit vectors are used to sample values from the hardware models, and to represent data that is transferred to hardware during simulations.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Common Lisp provides multi-dimensional bit arrays.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A one-dimensional `bit-vector` implementation is provided as a special case of the built-in `array`, acting in a dual capacity as a class and a type specifier.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit arrays (and thus bit vectors) relies on the general `make-array` function to be configured with an element type of `bit`, which optionally permits a bit vector to be designated as dynamically resizable.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] The `bit-vector`, however, is not infinite in extent.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] A more restricted `simple-bit-vector` type exists, which explicitly excludes the dynamic characteristics.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Bit vectors are represented as, and can be constructed in a more concise fashion by, the *reader macro* `#**bits*`.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] In addition to the general functions applicable to all arrays, dedicated operations exist for bit arrays.
[src:y-fast-trie/bit-array] Single bits may be accessed and modified using the `bit` and `sbit` functions and an extensive number of logical operations is supported.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] In computer science, a **fusion tree** is a type of tree data structure that implements an associative array on w-bit integers on a finite universe, where each of the input integers has size less than 2w and is non-negative.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] When operating on a collection of n key–value pairs, it uses *O*(*n*) space and performs searches in *O*(log*w* *n*) time, which is asymptotically faster than a traditional self-balancing binary search tree, and also better than the van Emde Boas tree for large values of w.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] It achieves this speed by using certain constant-time operations that can be done on a machine word.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Fusion trees were invented in 1990 by Michael Fredman and Dan Willard.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Several advances have been made since Fredman and Willard's original 1990 paper.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] A dynamic version of fusion trees using hash tables was proposed in 1996 which matched the original structure's *O*(log*w* *n*) runtime in expectation.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Another dynamic version using exponential tree was proposed in 2007 which yields worst-case runtimes of *O*(log*w* *n* + log log *n*) per operation.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Finally, it was shown that dynamic fusion trees can perform each operation in *O*(log*w* *n*) time deterministically.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This data structure implements add key, remove key, search key, and predecessor (next smaller value) and successor (next larger value) search operations for a given key.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The partial result of most significant bit locator in constant time has also helped further research.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Fusion trees utilize word-level parallelism to be efficient, performing computation on several small integers, stored in a single machine word, simultaneously to reduce the number of total operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] A fusion tree is essentially a B-tree with branching factor of *w*1/5 (any small exponent is also possible as it will not have a great impact on the height of the tree), which gives it a height of *O*(log*w* *n*).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] To achieve the desired runtimes for updates and queries, the fusion tree must be able to search a node containing up to *w*1/5 keys in constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This is done by compressing ("sketching") the keys so that all can fit into one machine word, which in turn allows comparisons to be done in parallel.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] So, a series of computations involving sketching, parallel comparison and most significant bit index locator, help reach the required solution.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Sketching is the method by which each w-bit key at a node containing k keys is compressed into only *k* − 1 bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Each key x may be thought of as a path in the full binary tree of height w starting at the root and ending at the leaf corresponding to x.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This path can be processed by recursively searching the left child of *i* if the *ith* bit is 0, and the right child if it is 1, generally, until all bits are scanned.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] To distinguish two paths, it suffices to look at their branching point (the first bit where any two keys differ).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] As there are a maximum of *k* keys, there will not be more than *k-1* branching points, which means that no more than *k-1* bits are required to identify a key.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] And hence, no sketch will have more than *k-1* bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] An important property of the sketch function is that it preserves the order of the keys.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] That is, sketch(*x*) < sketch(*y*) for any two keys *x* < *y*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] So, for the entire range of keys, sketch(x0)<sketch(x1)<...<sketch(xk-1) because if the binary-tree-like path is followed, the nodes will be ordered in such a manner that x0<x1<...<xk-1.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] With only standard word operations, such as those of the C programming language, it is difficult to directly compute the perfect sketch of a key in constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Instead, the sketch bits can be packed into a range of size at most *r*4, using bitwise AND and multiplication, called the approximate sketch, which does have all the important bits but also some additional useless bits spread out in a predictable pattern.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The bitwise AND operation serves as a mask to remove all these non-sketch bits from the key, while the multiplication shifts the sketch bits into a small range.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Like the "perfect" sketch, the approximate sketch also preserves the order of the keys and means that sketch(x0)<sketch(x1)<...<sketch(xk-1).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Some preprocessing is needed to determine the correct multiplication constant.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Each sketch bit in location *b**i* will get shifted to *b**i* + *m**i* via a multiplication by *m* = $\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{r}$ 2*m**i*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] *b**i* + *m**i* is a strictly increasing function of *i*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] That is, the order of the sketch bits is preserved even in x'.m.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] That is, the sketch bits are packed into a range of size at most *r*4, where r ≤ O(w1/5).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] An inductive argument shows how the *m**i* can be constructed.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Then pick the smallest integer *m**t* such that both properties (1) and (2) are satisfied.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Thus, there are less than *tr*2 ≤ *r*3 values that *m**t* must avoid.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Multiply the key by the predetermined constant *m* as calculated above.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This operation actually requires two machine words, but this can still be done in constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Mask out all but the shifted sketch bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] These are now contained in a contiguous block of at most *r*4 < *w*4/5 bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The purpose of the compression achieved by sketching is to allow all of the keys to be stored in one *w*-bit word.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Here, all sketch words are clubbed together in one string by prepending a set bit to each of them.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] We can assume that the sketch function uses exactly *b* ≤ *r*4 bits.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Then each block uses 1 + *b* ≤ *w*4/5 bits, and since *k* ≤ *w*1/5, the total number of bits in the node sketch is at most *w*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] A brief notational aside: for a bit string *s* and nonnegative integer *m*, let *s**m* denote the concatenation of *s* to itself *m* times.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] If *t* is also a bit string, *st* denotes the concatenation of *t* to *s*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The node sketch makes it possible to search the keys for any *b*-bit integer *y*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Let *z* = (0*y*)*k*, which can be computed in constant time (multiply *y* by the constant (0*b*1)*k*), to make it as long as the node sketch such that each word in the node sketch can be compared with the query integer *y* in one operation, demonstrating word-level parallelism.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] If *y* were 5 bits long, it would be multiplied by 000001....000001 to get sketch(y)k.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The difference between sketch(xi) and 0y results in the leading bit for each block to be 1, if and only if sketch(y) $\leq$ sketch(xi).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Take the bitwise AND of the difference and the constant (10*b*)*k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This clears all but the leading bit of each block.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Find the most significant bit of the result, to identify the exact index of transition from elements with sketch smaller than the query sketch to those greater than the query sketch.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Compute *i,* the rank of the sketch, using the fact that the leading bit of the *i*-th block has index *i*(*b*+1).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Unfortunately, this does give the exact predecessor or successor of *q*, because the location of the sketch of *q* among the sketches of all the values may not be the same as the location of *q* in all the actual values.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] What is true is that, among all of the keys, either *x**i*-1 or *x**i* has the longest common prefix with *q*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This is because any key *y* with a longer common prefix with *q* would also have more sketch bits in common with *q*, and thus `sketch`(*y*) would be closer to `sketch`(*q*) than any `sketch`(*x**j*).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The length longest common prefix between two *w*-bit integers *a* and *b* can be computed in constant time by finding the most significant bit of the bitwise XOR between *a* and *b*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This can then be used to mask out all but the longest common prefix.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Note that *p* identifies exactly where *q* branches off from the set of keys.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] If the next bit of *q* is 0, then the successor of *q* is contained in the *p*1 subtree, and if the next bit of *q* is 1, then the predecessor of *q* is contained in the *p*0 subtree.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Compute the longest common prefix *p* of *q* and either *x**i*-1 or *x**i* (taking the longer of the two).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Let *l*-1 be the length of the longest common prefix *p*.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Use parallel comparison to search for the predecessor of `sketch`(*e*).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Once either the predecessor or successor of *q* is found, the exact position of *q* among the set of keys is determined.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] An application of fusion trees to hash tables was given by Willard, who describes a data structure for hashing in which an outer-level hash table with hash chaining is combined with a fusion tree representing each hash chain.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] In hash chaining, in a hash table with a constant load factor, the average size of a chain is constant, but additionally with high probability all chains have size *O*(log *n* / log log *n*), where n is the number of hashed items.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] This chain size is small enough that a fusion tree can handle searches and updates within it in constant time per operation.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] Therefore, the time for all operations in the data structure is constant with high probability.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] More precisely, with this data structure, for every inverse-quasipolynomial probability *p*(*n*) = exp((log *n*)*O*(1)), there is a constant C such that the probability that there exists an operation that exceeds time C is at most *p*(*n*).
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] The computational model for the Fusion Tree algorithm is a Word RAM with a specific instruction set, including arithmetic instructions - addition, subtraction and multiplication (all performed modulo 2*w*) and Boolean operations - bitwise AND, NOT etc.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] A double-precision multiplication instruction is also included.
[src:y-fast-trie/fusion-tree] It has been shown that removal of the latter instruction makes it impossible to sort faster than *O*(*n* log *n*), unless it is permitted to use memory space of nearly 2*w* words (in contrast to linear space used by Fusion Trees), or include other instructions instead.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] In computer science, a **radix tree** (also **radix trie** or **compact prefix tree** or **compressed trie**) is a data structure that represents a space-optimized trie (prefix tree) in which each node that is the only child is merged with its parent.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The number of children of every internal node is at most the radix r of the radix tree, where r = 2x for some integer x ≥ 1.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees, edges can be labeled with sequences of elements as well as single elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This makes radix trees much more efficient for small sets (especially if the strings are long) and for sets of strings that share long prefixes.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees (where whole keys are compared *en masse* from their beginning up to the point of inequality), the key at each node is compared chunk-of-bits by chunk-of-bits, where the quantity of bits in that chunk at that node is the radix r of the radix trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] When r is 2, the radix trie is binary (i.e., compare that node's 1-bit portion of the key), which minimizes sparseness at the expense of maximizing trie depth—i.e., maximizing up to conflation of nondiverging bit-strings in the key.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] When r ≥ 4 is a power of 2, then the radix trie is an r-ary trie, which lessens the depth of the radix trie at the expense of potential sparseness.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] As an optimization, edge labels can be stored in constant size by using two pointers to a string (for the first and last elements).
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Note that although the examples in this article show strings as sequences of characters, the type of the string elements can be chosen arbitrarily; for example, as a bit or byte of the string representation when using multibyte character encodings or Unicode.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Radix trees are useful for constructing associative arrays with keys that can be expressed as strings.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] They find particular application in the area of IP routing, where the ability to contain large ranges of values with a few exceptions is particularly suited to the hierarchical organization of IP addresses.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] They are also used for inverted indexes of text documents in information retrieval.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Radix trees support insertion, deletion, and searching operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Insertion adds a new string to the trie while trying to minimize the amount of data stored.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Deletion removes a string from the trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Searching operations include (but are not necessarily limited to) exact lookup, find predecessor, find successor, and find all strings with a prefix.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] All of these operations are O(*k*) where k is the maximum length of all strings in the set, where length is measured in the quantity of bits equal to the radix of the radix trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The lookup operation determines if a string exists in a trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Most operations modify this approach in some way to handle their specific tasks.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] For instance, the node where a string terminates may be of importance.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This operation is similar to tries except that some edges consume multiple elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The following pseudo code assumes that these methods and members exist.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] To insert a string, we search the tree until we can make no further progress.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] At this point we either add a new outgoing edge labeled with all remaining elements in the input string, or if there is already an outgoing edge sharing a prefix with the remaining input string, we split it into two edges (the first labeled with the common prefix) and proceed.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This splitting step ensures that no node has more children than there are possible string elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Several cases of insertion are shown below.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] It is assumed that edges can be labelled with empty strings to terminate strings where necessary and that the root has no incoming edge.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] To delete a string x from a tree, we first locate the leaf representing x.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Then, assuming x exists, we remove the corresponding leaf node.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] If the parent of our leaf node has only one other child, then that child's incoming label is appended to the parent's incoming label and the child is removed.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The data structure was invented in 1968 by Donald R.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Morrison, with whom it is primarily associated, and by Gernot Gwehenberger.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Donald Knuth, pages 498–500 in Volume III of The Art of Computer Programming, calls these "Patricia's trees", presumably after the acronym in the title of Morrison's paper: "PATRICIA - Practical Algorithm to Retrieve Information Coded in Alphanumeric".
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Today, Patricia trees are seen as radix trees with radix equals 2, which means that each bit of the key is compared individually and each node is a two-way (i.e., left versus right) branch.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Unlike balanced trees, radix trees permit lookup, insertion, and deletion in O(*k*) time rather than O(log *n*).
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This does not seem like an advantage, since normally *k* ≥ log *n*, but in a balanced tree every comparison is a string comparison requiring O(*k*) worst-case time, many of which are slow in practice due to long common prefixes (in the case where comparisons begin at the start of the string).
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] In a trie, all comparisons require constant time, but it takes *m* comparisons to look up a string of length *m*.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Radix trees can perform these operations with fewer comparisons, and require many fewer nodes.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Radix trees also share the disadvantages of tries, however: as they can only be applied to strings of elements or elements with an efficiently reversible mapping to strings, they lack the full generality of balanced search trees, which apply to any data type with a total ordering.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] A reversible mapping to strings can be used to produce the required total ordering for balanced search trees, but not the other way around.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This can also be problematic if a data type only provides a comparison operation, but not a (de)serialization operation.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Hash tables are commonly said to have expected O(1) insertion and deletion times, but this is only true when considering computation of the hash of the key to be a constant-time operation.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] When hashing the key is taken into account, hash tables have expected O(*k*) insertion and deletion times, but may take longer in the worst case depending on how collisions are handled.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Radix trees have worst-case O(*k*) insertion and deletion.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The successor/predecessor operations of radix trees are also not implemented by hash tables.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] A common extension of radix trees uses two colors of nodes, "black" and "white".
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] To check if a given string is stored in the tree, the search starts from the top and follows the edges of the input string until no further progress can be made.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] If the search string is consumed and the final node is a black node, the search has failed; if it is white, the search has succeeded.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This makes possible to add a large range of strings with a common prefix to the tree, using white nodes, then remove a small set of "exceptions" in a space-efficient manner by *inserting* them using black nodes.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The **HAT-trie** is a cache-conscious data structure based on radix trees that offers efficient string storage and retrieval, and ordered iterations.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Performance, with respect to both time and space, is comparable to the cache-conscious hashtable.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] A **PATRICIA** trie is a special variant of the radix 2 (binary) trie, in which rather than explicitly store every bit of every key, the nodes store only the position of the first bit which differentiates two sub-trees.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] During traversal the algorithm examines the indexed bit of the search key and chooses the left or right sub-tree as appropriate.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Notable features of the PATRICIA trie include that the trie only requires one node to be inserted for every unique key stored, making PATRICIA much more compact than a standard binary trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Also, since the actual keys are no longer explicitly stored it is necessary to perform one full key comparison on the indexed record in order to confirm a match.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] In this respect PATRICIA bears a certain resemblance to indexing using a hash table.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The **adaptive radix tree** is a radix tree variant that integrates adaptive node sizes to the radix tree.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] One major drawback of the usual radix trees is the use of space, because it uses a constant node size in every level.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] The major difference between the radix tree and the adaptive radix tree is its variable size for each node based on the number of child elements, which grows while adding new entries.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] Hence, the adaptive radix tree leads to a better use of space without reducing its speed.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] A common practice is to relax the criteria of disallowing parents with only one child in situations where the parent represents a valid key in the data set.
[src:y-fast-trie/radix-tree] This variant of radix tree achieves a higher space efficiency than the one which only allows internal nodes with at least two children.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] A **van Emde Boas tree** (Dutch pronunciation: [vɑn ˈɛmdə ˈboːɑs]), also known as a **vEB tree** or **van Emde Boas priority queue**, is a tree data structure which implements an associative array with *m*-bit integer keys.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] It was invented by a team led by Dutch computer scientist Peter van Emde Boas in 1975.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] It performs all operations in *O*(log *m*) time (assuming that an m bit operation can be performed in constant time), or equivalently in $O(\log \log M)$ time, where $M=2^{m}$ is the largest element that can be stored in the tree.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The parameter M is not to be confused with the actual number of elements stored in the tree, by which the performance of other tree data-structures is often measured.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The standard vEB tree has an unideal space efficiency of $O(M)$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] For example, for storing 32-bit integers (i.e., when $m=32$ ), it requires $M=2^{32}$ bits of storage.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] To resolve this, vEB trees can be modified to achieve $O(n\log M)$ space, or similar data structures with equivalent asymptotic time efficiency and space efficiency of $O(n)$ (where n is the number of stored elements) can be used.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] A vEB tree also supports the operations *Minimum* and *Maximum*, which return the minimum and maximum element stored in the tree respectively.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] These both run in $O(1)$ time, since the minimum and maximum element are stored as attributes in each tree.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] A vEB tree T over the universe $\{0,\ldots ,M-1\}$ has a root node that stores an array T.children of length ${\sqrt {M}}$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] T.children[i] is a pointer to a vEB tree that is responsible for the values $\{i{\sqrt {M}},\ldots ,(i+1){\sqrt {M}}-1\}$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Additionally, *T* stores two values T.min and T.max as well as an auxiliary vEB tree T.aux.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Data is stored in a vEB tree as follows: The smallest value currently in the tree is stored in T.min and largest value is stored in T.max.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Note that T.min is not stored anywhere else in the vEB tree, while T.max is.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If *T* is empty then we use the convention that T.max=−1 and T.min=M.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Any other value x is stored in the subtree T.children[i] where $i=\lfloor x/{\sqrt {M}}\rfloor$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The auxiliary tree T.aux keeps track of which children are non-empty, so T.aux contains the value j if and only if T.children[j] is non-empty.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The operation FindNext(T, x) that searches for the successor of an element *x* in a vEB tree proceeds as follows: If *x*<T.min then the search is complete, and the answer is T.min.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If x≥T.max then the next element does not exist, return M.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, let $i=\lfloor x/{\sqrt {M}}\rfloor$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If x < T.children[i].max, then the value being searched for is contained in T.children[i], so the search proceeds recursively in T.children[i].
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, we search for the successor of the value *i* in T.aux.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives us the index *j* of the first subtree that contains an element larger than *x*.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The algorithm then returns T.children[j].min.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The element found on the children level needs to be composed with the high bits to form a complete next element.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Note that, in any case, the algorithm performs $O(1)$ work and then possibly recurses on a subtree over a universe of size $M^{1/2}$ (an $m/2$ bit universe).
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives a recurrence for the running time of $T(m)=T(m/2)+O(1)$ , which resolves to $O(\log m)=O(\log \log M)$ .
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x<T.min then we insert T.min into the subtree i responsible for T.min and then set T.min = x.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x>T.max then we insert x into the subtree i responsible for x and then set T.max = x.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, T.min< x < T.max so we insert x into the subtree i responsible for x.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If T.children[i] was previously empty, then we also insert i into T.aux.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The key to the efficiency of this procedure is that inserting an element into an empty vEB tree takes *O*(1) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] So, even though the algorithm sometimes makes two recursive calls, this only occurs when the first recursive call was into an empty subtree.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives the same running time recurrence of ⁠ $T(m)=T(m/2)+O(1)$ ⁠ as before.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Deletion from vEB trees is the trickiest of the operations.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x == T.min then we need to find the second-smallest value *y* in the vEB tree, delete it from its current location, and set T.min=y.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The second-smallest value *y* is T.children[T.aux.min].min, so it can be found in *O*(1) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] We delete *y* from the subtree that contains it.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If x≠T.min and x≠T.max then we delete x from the subtree T.children[i] that contains *x*.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] If x == T.max then we will need to find the second-largest value *y* in the vEB tree and set T.max=y.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] We start by deleting x as in previous case.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Then value *y* is either T.min or T.children[T.aux.max].max, so it can be found in *O*(1) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] In any of the above cases, if we delete the last element *x* or *y* from any subtree T.children[i] then we also delete *i* from T.aux.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Again, the efficiency of this procedure hinges on the fact that deleting from a vEB tree that contains only one element takes only constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] In particular, the second Delete call only executes if *x* was the only element in T.children[i] prior to the deletion.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The assumption that log *m* is an integer is unnecessary.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The operations $x{\sqrt {M}}$ and $x{\bmod {\sqrt {M}}}$ can be replaced by taking only higher-order ⌈*m*/2⌉ and the lower-order ⌊*m*/2⌋ bits of x, respectively.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] On any existing machine, this is more efficient than division or remainder computations.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] In practical implementations, especially on machines with *shift-by-k* and *find first zero* instructions, performance can further be improved by switching to a bit array once m equal to the word size (or a small multiple thereof) is reached.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Since all operations on a single word are constant time, this does not affect the asymptotic performance, but it does avoid the majority of the pointer storage and several pointer dereferences, achieving a significant practical savings in time and space with this trick.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] An optimization of vEB trees is to discard empty subtrees.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This makes vEB trees quite compact when they contain many elements, because no subtrees are created until something needs to be added to them.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Initially, each element added creates about log(*m*) new trees containing about *m*/2 pointers all together.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] As the tree grows, more and more subtrees are reused, especially the larger ones.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The implementation described above uses pointers and occupies a total space of *O*(*M*) = *O*(2*m*), proportional to the size of the key universe.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] One can show that *S*(*M*) = *O*(*M*) by induction.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] The *O*(*M*) space usage of vEB trees is an enormous overhead unless a large fraction of the universe of keys is being stored.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This is one reason why vEB trees are not popular in practice.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This limitation can be addressed by changing the array used to store children to another data structure.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] One possibility is to use only a fixed number of bits per level, which results in a trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Alternatively, each array may be replaced by a hash table, reducing the space to *O*(*n* log log *M*) (where n is the number of elements stored in the data structure) at the expense of making the data structure randomized.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] x-fast tries and the more complicated y-fast tries have comparable update and query times to vEB trees and use randomized hash tables to reduce the space used. x-fast tries use *O*(*n* log *M*) space while y-fast tries use *O*(*n*) space.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Fusion trees are another type of tree data structure that implements an associative array on w-bit integers on a finite universe.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] They use word-level parallelism and bit manipulation techniques to achieve *O*(log*w* *n*) time for predecessor/successor queries and updates, where *w* is the word size.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Fusion trees use *O*(*n*) space and can be made dynamic with hashing or exponential trees.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Lenhof and Smid present a variant of the vEB tree which uses space *O*(*n*) and take *O*(1) expected amortized time for inserting an element, under the restriction that insertions are in increasing order; in other words, the inserted element is always the new maximum.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This structure uses dynamic perfect hashing to implement the tree in small space and moreover decrease the size of the tree by a log log *M* factor by keeping at the leaves buckets of size log log *M*.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] A space-efficient and partially persistent version of vEB trees was presented by Dietz and Raman.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] This version uses *O*(*n*) space, and supports an insert in the current version in *O*(log log *M*) amortized and expected time, while a query on any version remains *O*(log log *M*).
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] There is a verified implementation in Isabelle (proof assistant).
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Both functional correctness and time bounds are proved.
[src:y-fast-trie/van-emde-boas-tree] Efficient imperative Standard ML code can be generated.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] In computer science, an **x-fast trie** is a data structure for storing integers from a bounded domain.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] It supports exact and predecessor or successor queries in time *O*(log log *M*), using *O*(*n* log *M*) space, where *n* is the number of stored values and *M* is the maximum value in the domain.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] The structure was proposed by Dan Willard in 1982, along with the more complicated y-fast trie, as a way to improve the space usage of van Emde Boas trees, while retaining the *O*(log log *M*) query time.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] An x-fast trie is a bitwise trie: a binary tree where each subtree stores values whose binary representations start with a common prefix.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Each internal node is labeled with the common prefix of the values in its subtree and typically, the left child adds a 0 to the end of the prefix, while the right child adds a 1.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] The binary representation of an integer between 0 and *M* − 1 uses ⌈log2 *M*⌉ bits, so the height of the trie is *O*(log *M*).
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] All values in the x-fast trie are stored at the leaves.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Internal nodes are stored only if they have leaves in their subtree.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] If an internal node would have no left child, it stores a pointer to the smallest leaf in its right subtree instead, called a *descendant* pointer.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Likewise, if it would have no right child, it stores a pointer to the largest leaf in its left subtree.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Each leaf stores a pointer to its predecessor and successor, thereby forming a doubly linked list.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Finally, there is a hash table for each level that contains all the nodes on that level.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Together, these hash tables form the level-search structure (LSS).
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] To guarantee the worst-case query times, these hash tables should use dynamic perfect hashing or cuckoo hashing.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] The total space usage is *O*(*n* log *M*), since each element has a root-to-leaf path of length *O*(log *M*).
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Like van Emde Boas trees, x-fast tries support the operations of an *ordered associative array*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Finding the value associated with a key *k* that is in the data structure can be done in constant time by looking up *k* in *LSS*[0], which is a hash table on all the leaves.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] To find the successor or predecessor of a key *k*, we first find *A**k*, the lowest ancestor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] This is the node in the trie that has the longest common prefix with *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] To find *A**k*, we perform a binary search on the levels.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] We start at level *h*/2, where *h* is the height of the trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] On each level, we query the corresponding hash table in the level-search structure with the prefix of *k* of the right length.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] If a node with that prefix does not exist, we know that *A**k* must be at a higher level and we restrict our search to those.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] If a node with that prefix does exist, *A**k* can not be at a higher level, so we restrict our search to the current and lower levels.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Once we find the lowest ancestor of *k*, we know that it has leaves in one of its subtrees (otherwise it wouldn't be in the trie) and *k* should be in the other subtree.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Therefore, the descendant pointer points to the successor or the predecessor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Depending on which one we are looking for, we might have to take one step in the linked list to the next or previous leaf.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Since the trie has height *O*(log *M*), the binary search for the lowest ancestor takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] After that, the successor or predecessor can be found in constant time, so the total query time is *O*(log log *M*).
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] To insert a key-value pair (*k*, *v*), we first find the predecessor and successor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Then we create a new leaf for *k*, insert it in the linked list of leaves between the successor and predecessor, and give it a pointer to *v*.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Next, we walk from the root to the new leaf, creating the necessary nodes on the way down, inserting them into the respective hash tables and updating descendant pointers where necessary.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Since we have to walk down the entire height of the trie, this process takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] To delete a key *k*, we find its leaf using the hash table on the leaves.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] We remove it from the linked list, but remember which were the successor and predecessor.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Then we walk from the leaf to the root of the trie, removing all nodes whose subtree only contained *k* and updating the descendant pointers where necessary.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Descendant pointers that used to point to *k* will now point to either the successor or predecessor of *k*, depending on which subtree is missing.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Like insertion, this takes *O*(log *M*) time, as we have to walk through every level of the trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] Willard introduced x-fast tries largely as an introduction to y-fast tries, which provide the same query time, while using only *O*(*n*) space and allowing insertions and deletions in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/x-fast-trie] A compression technique similar to patricia tries can be used to significantly reduce the space usage of x-fast tries in practice.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] In computer science, a **y-fast trie** is a data structure for storing integers from a bounded domain.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] It supports exact and predecessor or successor queries in time *O*(log log *M*), using *O*(*n*) space, where *n* is the number of stored values and *M* is the maximum value in the domain.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] The structure was proposed by Dan Willard in 1983 to decrease the *O*(*n* log *M*) space used by an x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] A y-fast trie consists of two data structures: the top half is an x-fast trie and the lower half consists of a number of balanced binary trees.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] The keys are divided into groups of *O*(log *M*) consecutive elements and for each group a balanced binary search tree is created.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] To facilitate efficient insertion and deletion, each group contains at least (log *M*)/4 and at most 2 log *M* elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] For each balanced binary search tree a representative *r* is chosen.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] These representatives are stored in the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Initially, the representative of a tree will be an integer between the minimum and maximum element in its tree.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Since the x-fast trie stores *O*(*n* / log *M*) representatives and each representative occurs in *O*(log *M*) hash tables, this part of the y-fast trie uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] The balanced binary search trees store *n* elements in total which uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, in total a y-fast trie uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Like van Emde Boas trees and x-fast tries, y-fast tries support the operations of an *ordered associative array*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] A key *k* can be stored in either the tree of the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* or in the tree of the predecessor of *r* since the representative of a binary search tree need not be an element stored in its tree.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, one first finds the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Using this representative, one retrieves the predecessor of *r*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] These two representatives point to two balanced binary search trees, both of which one searches for *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finding the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie takes *O*(log log *M*).
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Using *r*, finding its predecessor takes constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Searching the two balanced binary search trees containing *O*(log *M*) elements each takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, a key *k* can be found, and its value retrieved, in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Similarly to the key *k* itself, its successor can be stored in either the tree of the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* or in the tree of the predecessor of *r*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, to find the successor of a key *k*, one first searches the x-fast trie for the smallest representative greater than *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Next, one uses this representative to retrieve its predecessor in the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] These two representatives point to two balanced binary search trees, which one searches for the successor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finding the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie takes *O*(log log *M*) time and using *r* to find its predecessor takes constant time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, the successor of a key *k* can be found, and its value retrieved, in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Searching for the predecessor of a key *k* is highly similar to finding its successor.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] One searches the x-fast trie for the largest representative *r* smaller than *k* and one uses *r* to retrieve its predecessor in the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finally, one searches the two balanced binary search trees of these two representatives for the predecessor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] To insert a new key/value pair (*k*, *v*), one first needs to determine in which balanced binary search tree one needs to insert *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] To this end, one finds the tree *T* containing the successor of *k*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] To ensure that all balanced binary search trees contain *O*(log *M*) elements, one splits *T* into two balanced binary trees and removes its representative from the x-fast trie if it contains more than 2 log *M* elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Each of the two new balanced binary search trees contains at most log *M* + 1 elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] One picks a representative for each tree and insert these into the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finding the successor of *k* takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Inserting *k* into a balanced binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements also takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Splitting a binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements can be done in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finally, inserting and deleting the three representatives takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] However, since one splits the tree at most once every *O*(log *M*) insertions and deletions, this takes constant amortized time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Therefore, inserting a new key/value pair takes *O*(log log *M*) amortized time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Deletions are very similar to insertions.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] One first finds the key *k* in one of the balanced binary search trees and delete it from this tree *T*.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] To ensure that all balanced binary search trees contain *O*(log *M*) elements, one merges *T* with the balanced binary search tree of its successor or predecessor if it contains less than (log *M*)/4 elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] The representatives of the merged trees are removed from the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] It is possible for the merged tree to contain more than 2 log *M* elements.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] If this is the case, the newly formed tree is split into two trees of about equal size.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Next, one picks a new representative for each of the new trees and one inserts these into the x-fast trie.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finding the key *k* takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Deleting *k* from a balanced binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements also takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Merging and possibly splitting the balanced binary search trees takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Finally, deleting the old representatives and inserting the new representatives into the x-fast trie takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Merging and possibly splitting the balanced binary search tree, however, is done at most once for every *O*(log *M*) insertions and deletions.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Hence, it takes constant amortized time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Therefore, deleting a key/value pair takes *O*(log log *M*) amortized time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Note that if the element we want to delete is a leaf of the X-fast trie, then we put a note saying that this number is here just to separate two binary search trees, and this number will not be returned.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] In this case, the number will not be actually removed.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] This will take *O*(1) time, and finding the key k takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:y-fast-trie/y-fast-trie] Therefore, the time complexity is *O*(log log *M*).
